1.1 Introduction

The following study was conducted to operationalize bike ride-sharing stations in Boston, Massachusetts. Boston has a city-wide goal of increasing bike usage by 400% by 2030. Towards that effort, the city has put substantial funding into infrastructure development of safer bike routes. The city has added an additional 50 new bikes share stations since 2019 and has held over 42 public meetings to determine where to add more. This study represents the kind of information that is necesary to facilitate public-private partnerships. Bluebikes is owned by the municipalities of Boston, Brookline, Cambridge, Somerville and Everet, but operated by a private company called Motivate. Analysis into this operation, therefore, would require a combination of publically availble data bout the spatial conditions of the bikeshare program, and data collected by the company on users. Becuase the program is publicly owned, Motivate publishes real-time data about the programs use.

The purpose of this study was to predict the demand of bikes among boston-based bike stations. In addition to learning to use time-space predictive modeling to address operational challenges, we learned how nuanced insights into the capacity of predictive models can be used for business strategy.

This model can be used to develop both a pro-active bike operations strategy and re-active strategy. Proactively, were we have accurately predicted the demand of bikes, we can develop a resource-intensive strategy for meeting this demand. In practice, this could be trucks with pre-determined routes and staffing. For the times when we seem to be consistently under-predicting, wecould develop a more re-active stragey like surge-pricing to intice customers to redistribute the bikes as needed. Either way, predictive models help us identify both constants and unknowns in the process.

6.1. Interpreting our predictions

This study has begun to predict the demand of bikeshare bikes in Boston, MA. Through temporal & spatial analysis, we have demonstrated that demand in certain stations can be identified and predicted. While the model did not create the accuracy needed for business use, the study demonstrates the type of spatial and temporal variables that impact the demand of bikes. Distance to metro stations and hospitals appear to be significant facotrs in determining the demand of bikes. Temporal factors such as day of the week are significant determminants of bike usage. Additional study would be needed to determine if the clusering observed are purely spatial reasons or if there are demographic considerations. For example - does the high demand for bikes near hospitals occur becasue there is a lack of available parking, or because of the demographics of the populations who work there? Analyis of this sort introduces the concepts of spatial and temporal intelligence in addition to operationalizing deicisons in public-private partnerships.
